{
  "texts": [
    "Projects that aggregate specialized medical data for diagnostic systems (Topol, 2019), simulate high-fidelity environments for robotics and autonomous vehicles (Dosovitskiy et al., 2017; Kalashnikov et al., 2018), or compile deep reinforcement learning benchmarks with realistic constraints (Bellemare et al., 2013; Dulac-Arnold et al., 2021) attest to the idea that harnessing robust datasets can be as determinative as algorithmic ingenuity or raw computational power.",
    "Despite the continued importance of parallel computing and innovative architectures, many cutting-edge successes now hinge on data strategy.",
    "The \"data-centric AI\" movement gained traction through collaborations between academic labs (e.g., Stanford's DAWN project) and industry partners in healthcare, automotive, and finance, where structured data pipelines and synthetic data initiatives (e.g., NVIDIA's DRIVESim) received dedicated research grants and created shared benchmarks.",
    "Researchers have championed \"data-centric AI\" (Ng, 2021), arguing that refining training sets, removing biases, filling in coverage gaps, or generating synthetic data to handle edge cases, often yields more improvement than adding layers to a neural network.",
    "This philosophy is closely related to the rise of foundation models (Bommasani et al., 2021), which are vast neural architectures that can be adapted to myriad tasks but require massive, carefully curated corpora to realize their full potential."
  ]
}